  "finch_name": "HTMLInterestForAttribute",
  "non_finch_justification": null,
  "ongoing_constraints": "None",
  "rollout_plan": 0,
  "rollout_plan_displayname": "Will ship enabled for all users",
  "motivation": "The `popover=hint` feature (https://chromestatus.com/feature/5073251081912320, shipped in M133) provides \"half\" of the features needed to build declarative tooltips, hovercards, and menus. The missing piece is the invocation of those UX elements on hover, keyboard activation, or long-press. This feature fills that gap.",
  "devtrial_instructions": null,
  "activation_risks": "There is a polyfill (https://github.com/mfreed7/interestfor) which can be used to mitigate a lack of browser support. See https://open-ui.org/components/interest-invokers.explainer/#touchscreen for more detail, but since users need to maintain access to the UA-provided  <a> long-press context menu, it isn’t possible for the polyfill to support touchscreen long-press without canceling the context menu. Importantly, however, due to this same limitation, almost no production sites today support touchscreen activation of hovercards. So the activation story should be fairly good: no loss of functionality on browsers relying on the polyfill, and an enhanced story on touchscreen for browsers natively supporting the feature.",
  "measurement": null,
  "availability_expectation": "Unknown, due to WebKit objections.",
  "adoption_expectation": "With the polyfill (https://github.com/mfreed7/interestfor), it is my hope that adoption can proceed for some sites before Baseline status. That remains to be seen.",
  "adoption_plan": null,
  "initial_public_proposal_url": "https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/10309",
  "explainer_links": [
    "https://open-ui.org/components/interest-invokers.explainer"
  ],
  "requires_embedder_support": false,
  "spec_link": "https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/11006",
  "api_spec": true,
  "automation_spec": false,
  "interop_compat_risks": "Note: There are interop issues due to WebKit. WebKit has expressed opposition (https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/10309#issuecomment-3266951344) to supporting the \"tooltip\" use case, citing the lack of \"a consistent and reliable way to get to tooltip-like information [on touchscreen]\". This is despite long-press being the de-facto standard for exactly that interaction pattern, for at least a decade if not longer. See, for example, UIKit's long-press documentation (https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/handling-long-press-gestures), the following comment (https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/10309#issuecomment-3267037840) on the standards issue, and a similar comment (https://github.com/WebKit/standards-positions/issues/305#issuecomment-2493546945) from a year ago which also did not receive a response by WebKit. In addition, WebKit's opinion states that they are unable to identify an interface mechanism for `interestfor` on spatial computing devices. I've suggested (https://github.com/WebKit/standards-positions/issues/305#issuecomment-2287429935) that one option is to mandate a particular behavior for these devices, but that comment was ignored.\n\nImportantly, the TAG review was marked Supportive (https://github.com/w3ctag/design-reviews/issues/1058) for this overall API proposal.\n",
  "all_platforms": true,
  "all_platforms_descr": null,
  "non_oss_deps": null,
  "anticipated_spec_changes": "Since WebKit is objecting to the feature, the HTML spec PR (https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/11006) cannot land. It's possible that in the future, when WebKit reviewers give it a review, they find things that they would like to change. Given all of the opportunities provided to them to give this feedback early, we should be highly reluctant to make such changes. However, they are at least possible.\n\nThe CSS specs have landed in drafts (https://drafts.csswg.org/css-ui-4/#interest and https://drafts.csswg.org/selectors/#interest-pseudos). Those were the result of active discussions in the CSSWG on multiple occasions, with significant feedback from the participants. So I would consider those to be lower risk of changing.",
  "security_risks": null,
  "ergonomics_risks": "The `popover=hint` API is a fairly important companion API to this one, providing a way to *not* close other unrelated `popover=auto` popover stacks when a tooltip UX is shown.",
  "wpt": true,
  "wpt_descr": "https://wpt.fyi/results/html/semantics/interestfor",
  "webview_risks": "Should not be any WebView risk. It's possible that if WebView apps suppress the context menu, then content that uses `interestfor` will not be available within those apps. However, presumably in such an app, the long press gesture is already being intercepted to provide a tooltip or app-provided menu, and that will continue to function.",
